My Meme

My Meme is a meme that took inspiration from a basic 4 square format meme but expresses my feelings about the activities that I would like to have been doing instead of all the code that I have been doing recently.

library(magick)

#I started my meme b looking at some classic cat memes and I took inspiration from the classic 4 square meme format.

#I loved cat memes so I decided to find two similar cats to use for my meme

#the Top squares are the writing and the two bottom squares are the images.

#top left Square aka the the activity I wish I was doing right now.

top_left_text <- image_blank(width = 200,
            height = 80,
            color = "#000000") %>%
  image_annotate(text = "ME WHEN PLAYING GAME",
                 color = "#ffffff",
                 size = 20,
                 font = "impact",
                 gravity = "center")

#top right Square aka the activity Im sadly doing right now

top_right_square <- image_blank(width = 200,
                                height = 80,
                                color = "#000000") %>% 
  image_annotate(text = "ME WHEN DOING CODE",
                 color = "#ffffff",
                 size = 20,
                 font = "impact",
                 gravity = "center")

#bottom left Square aka me if I was doing what I want to do

cat <- image_read("https://cdn.pixabay.com/photo/2013/07/12/19/22/cat-154642_960_720.png") %>%
  image_scale(200)

#Bottom right Square aka Me right now

madcat <- image_read("https://cdn.pixabay.com/photo/2013/07/12/19/22/cat-154641_960_720.png") %>%
  image_scale(200)

#Top Line Starting by combining the two squares with writing.

Lines_together <- c(top_left_text, top_right_square)
Top_line <- image_append(Lines_together)

#Bottom Line combining the bottom images
Cat_Together <- c(cat,madcat)
Bottom_line <- image_append(Cat_Together)

#Finished Product both lines combined.
Cat_meme <- c(Top_line, Bottom_line) %>%
  image_append(stack= TRUE) %>%
  image_scale(700)

Cat_meme

image_write(Cat_meme, "Cat_meme.png")

My animated GIF

I wanted to create a similar GIF as the breathing give in lab 2 with a count down instead of counting to 4 so I created a bomb countdown which was harder to code as I wanted to use a electric clock format of 00:05 but this proved not possible with my current skill, the GIF was supposed to be a slow countdown to a more of an annoying joke.

library(magick)
#GIF will be a bomb timer
counter <- 5 : 0 %>% as.character()

#creating each counter frame, will start from 5 and count down to 0

frame1 <- image_blank(color = "black", width = 800, height = 500) %>%
  image_annotate(text = counter[1],color = "red", size = 100, gravity = "center")

frame2 <- image_blank(color = "black", width = 800, height = 500) %>%
  image_annotate(text = counter[2],color = "red", size = 100, gravity = "center")

frame3 <- image_blank(color = "black", width = 800, height = 500) %>%
  image_annotate(text = counter[3],color = "red", size = 100, gravity = "center")

frame4 <- image_blank(color = "black", width = 800, height = 500) %>%
  image_annotate(text = counter[4],color = "red", size = 100, gravity = "center")

frame5 <- image_blank(color = "black", width = 800, height = 500) %>%
  image_annotate(text = counter[5],color = "red", size = 100, gravity = "center")

frame6<- image_blank(color = "black", width = 800, height = 500) %>%
  image_annotate(text = "BOOM!",color = "red", size = 200, gravity = "center")

frame7 <- image_blank(color = "black", width = 800, height = 500) %>%
  image_annotate(text = "HAHAHA did I scare you?",color = "red", size = 70, gravity = "center")

#all frames together
frames <- c(frame1,frame2,frame3,frame4,frame5,frame6,frame7)

#Sadly this GIF is a lot simpler than I would like it to be but everyy one of these frames has been a pain in the ass to write so here it is.

#final GIF
final_GIF <- image_animate(frames, fps = 1)

final_GIF

image_write(final_GIF, "final_GIF.gif")
